h3. Problem Definition
The insert query to cwd_granted_perm written in the page [Restoring Passwords To Recover Admin User Rights|https://confluence.atlassian.com/crowdkb/restoring-passwords-to-recover-admin-user-rights-283642653.html] is outdated. The query fails due to a lack of a column.
{code:sql}
INSERT INTO cwd_granted_perm(ID, created_date, permission_id, group_mapping) 
VALUES (999999, '<current time (i.e. 2015-09-25 12:08:00)', 2, 898990);
{code}

h3. Suggested Solution

It should have app_dir_mapping_id column in its query.
{code:sql}
insert into cwd_granted_perm (id, created_date, permission_id, app_dir_mapping_id, group_name)
 values (999999, '<current time (i.e. 2015-09-25 12:08:00)', 2, <id from step "e" >,898990);
{code}

The Crowd directory synchronisation with LDAP does not log detail LDAP request with the directory field which would be useful for System Administrator to debug the directory synchronisation issue.

Setting the following line in <CROWD-INSTALL>/crowd-webapp/WEB-INF/classes/*log4j.properties* doesn't log detail LDAP request :
{code}
log4j.logger.com.atlassian.crowd.manager.application.ApplicationServiceGeneric=DEBUG
log4j.logger.com.atlassian.crowd.directory.SpringLDAPConnector=DEBUG
{code}

h3. Environment
 - Crowd 3.1.1;
 - Confluence 6.6.0;
 - Two different LDAP servers *;

 * Tested with AD and ApacheDS. Should work with just different UOs on the same LDAP, but haven't tested yet.

h3. Prepare the environment
 # Create a user in each LDAP server with the *same username* but different details - e.g. email and password;
 ** Username: *bob*
 # Set two *Delegated authentication directories* in Crowd;
 ** *Internal Users* and *External Users*
 # Create groups into each directory;
 ** *internal-users* and *external-users*
 # Connect Confluence and Crowd;
 # Add *Internal Users* and *External Users* (in this order) to the Confluence connection in Crowd;
 !directories list.png|thumbnail!
 # (i) Have the users log into Crowd (so they are stored in the database) and add them to the respective groups; or *Automatically assign* in the application settings;
 !internal-users crowd.png|thumbnail!
 !external-users crowd.png|thumbnail!

h3. Steps to reproduce
 # Log in to Confluence with the credentials of *Internal Users*
 ** Check user details in Confluence - all good (/) - expected;
 !bob in confluence - internal.png|thumbnail!
 # Log Out;
 # *Disable 'bob' in the LDAP Server named as Internal Users*;
 # Log in to Confluence with the same credentials from Internal Users - (!) "Sorry, your username and/or password are incorrect. Please try again."
{code:java|title=Crowd log}
2018-01-16 20:41:42,016 http-nio-8095-exec-18 INFO [crowd.manager.application.ApplicationServiceGeneric] Invalid credentials for user bob in directory External Users (753667), aborting
{code}
{code:java|title=Confluence log}
2018-01-16 20:41:42,036 WARN [http-nio-8090-exec-9] [atlassian.seraph.auth.DefaultAuthenticator] login login : 'bob' tried to login but they do not have USE permission or weren't found. Deleting remember me cookie.
 -- referer: http://localhost:8090/dologin.action | url: /dologin.action | traceId: 8e24ec6ca0152650
{code}
 # (!) Notice how Crowd identifies that the user couldn't be found within 'Internal Users' (1st position) and authenticated against 'External Users' - even though CWD-2478 says that Crowd can't handle such situation very well.
 # Enter the credentials of External Users in Confluence;
 ** Check user details - Email (/) Groups (x) still the same groups from 'Internal Users';
 !bob in confluence - external.png|thumbnail!

h3. Additional tests
 - Synchronizing the Crowd directory in Confluence makes the Email revert back to 'Bob@internal.org' and the groups remain the same. Logging in again updates the email.

 - If we uncheck *Active* in the Internal User's details in Crowd console and sync the directory in Confluence, Confluence set the user as Disabled.
However, logging in again with credentials from External Users, set the details back to Step 6 above.

 - This is only reproducible with Delegated type. Testing with Connectors won't let 'bob' from subsequent directories to log in Confluence.

Since Crowd 2.9.1, it does support use of Gravatar. However, the parameter is not yet officially documented.

related ticket : -CWD-4473-

To enable Crowd to use custom Gravatar server, add  the parameter below to JVM Property into {{$crowd_install/apache-tomcat/bin/setenv.sh|bat}}:
{code:java}
web.avatar.baseurl
{code}

For example:
{code}
JAVA_OPTS="-Xms128m -Xmx512m -Dfile.encoding=UTF-8 -Dweb.avatar.baseurl=https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ $JAVA_OPTS"
{code}
This require Crowd to be restarted for it to take effect.
